SIMPLE: tune
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tune
<hw>Tune</hw> <pr>(t⟦umac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A variant of
<ets>tone</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sound; a note; a tone.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>tune</xex> of your voices.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A rhythmical,
melodious, symmetrical series of tones for one voice or instrument, or
for any number of voices or instruments in unison, or two or more such
series forming parts in harmony; a melody; an air; <as>as, a merry
<ex>tune</ex>; a mournful <ex>tune</ex>; a slow <ex>tune</ex>; a psalm
<ex>tune</ex>. See <er>Air</er>.</as></def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The state
of giving the proper sound or sounds; just intonation; harmonious
accordance; pitch of the voice or an instrument; adjustment of the parts
of an instrument so as to harmonize with itself or with others; <as>as,
the piano, or the organ, is not in <ex>tune</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like sweet bells jangled, out of <qex>tune</qex> and harsh.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Order; harmony; concord; fit disposition, temper, or
humor; right mood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A child will learn three times as much when he is in
<qex>tune</qex>, as when he . . . is dragged unwillingly to [his
task].</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tune</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tune
<hw>Tune</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tuned</conjf> <pr>(t⟦umac⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tuning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put into a state
adapted to produce the proper sounds; to harmonize, to cause to be in
tune; to correct the tone of; <as>as, to <ex>tune</ex> a piano or a
violin</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ <xex>Tune</xex> your harps.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1551 pr=PI -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give tone to; to attune; to adapt in style of
music; to make harmonious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For now to sorrow must I <qex>tune</qex> my song.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sing with melody or harmony.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fountains, and ye, that warble, as ye flow,⟦br⟧
Melodious murmurs, warbling <qex>tune</qex> his praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put into a proper state or disposition.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tune</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tune
<hw>Tune</hw> <pr>(t⟦umac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
form one sound to another; to form accordant musical sounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whilst <qex>tuning</qex> to the water's fall,⟦br⟧
The small birds sang to her.</q> <rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter inarticulate harmony with the voice; to
sing without pronouncing words; to hum.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuneful</ent>⟦br⟧
